uld be, KPHC took the approach below to balance the risk of overdosing against the risk of underdosing.    \n\nBased on the patients weight, KPHC will limit the initial infusion dose of non-cardiac heparin to 1500 Units/hour for females and 2000 Units/hour for males.\n\nDecision support language (located at top of order set under \"criteria of use\") has been added to both heparin order sets (cardiac and non-cardiac) to guide optimal physician practices.  This was taken from the KPNC ACS Guideline and regional \"paper\" order templates for IV heparin.  Other change includes removal of aPTT level at baseline (no longer needed).',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2198,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Phil Lee','',3105644,NULL,'OS Cardiac Heparin OS: Revision',NULL,'OS',NULL,'0',NULL,'0','L','R','H','S','Cardiac Heparin',NULL,'','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NOWRK','Res','CARD','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Content','Order Set - MD','','L','N','N',' ',NULL,'NR',' ','N','MEDSURG','0','0','0','0','0','0','0',NULL,NULL,'2009-06-17 13:48:55','2009-07-21 13:49:55','2009-07-21 08:41:18','2009-07-28 14:09:52','2008-11-13 09:27:44',' ','Phil Lee','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'','Herb Szeto','Anne Foss-Durant',988,NULL,201,201,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2008-11-18 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-03-16 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-03-24 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-03-24 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-06-17 00:00:00','2009-05-20 00:00:00','2009-05-08 00:00:00','2009-05-22 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'2009-06-08 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-06-10 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-06-17 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'2009-06-22 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-06-24 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-06-24 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2008-11-18 08:46:00','2009-06-17 01:40:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OS Cardiac Heparin OS: Revision\n\nRevisions include addition of criteria of use and revisions to lab orders.\n\nScreenshots will be used later with the changes (Emily C Foo)\n\nBackground/Context\nHeparin is a high risk medication with narrow therapeutic window and risk of potential morbidity and mortality. It is vitally important that adult cardiac patients receive lower dose \"cardiac\" heparin.  When cardiac patients receive higher dose \"non-cardiac\" heparin, along with other antithrombotic agents such as  aspirin, fibrinolytic therapy like TNKase, integrilin, etc, they have a significantly higher chance of bleeding complications and mortality.  Higher dose \"non-cardiac\" heparin is used to treat deep venous thrombosis and pulmonary embolism in patients who are NOT receiving aspirin or other antithrombotic agents. Recommended language also taken from Chiefs of Neurology that patients with acute stroke should generally not be given heparin, and in rare circumstances when this is beneficial, an intravenous bolus should not be given.\n\nDecision support language (located at top of order set under \"criteria of use\") has been added to both heparin order sets (cardiac and non-cardiac) to guide optimal physician practices.  This was taken from the KPNC ACS Guideline and regional \"paper\" order templates for IV heparin.  Other change includes removal of aPTT level at baseline (no longer needed).\n\nThe new PRL enhancement to inpatient health connect provides an additional safety feature for the weight-based dosing to not exceed the maximum recommended doses of IV heparin (eg. for cardiac patients, maximum bolus of 4000 units and 1000 units/hour infusion).  This is not part of the order set change but is included here as background information.',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2199,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Phil Lee','',3105537,NULL,'OS H