list Haldol with a route option of intravenous, so if our goal is to drop all references to IV Haldol then none of these Order sets can be considered until region fixes them. 2/24/09 Upper Extremity Ortho \n\nPer Linda Daniel, A FDA alert has come out that states Haloperidol is not approved for Intravenous Use.  QT prolongation have been observed in patients recieving this drug IV\n\nOur comfort care orders state for Delirium:  Haldol 2mg IV every 1 hour as needed.\n\nWe have had some discussion about the need to use Haldol IV for severe delirium, paitent on comfort care so not on tele. Questions can we investigate what the new health connect orders are-Vicki can you share with us\nShould we pull the orders out-But what if Haldol is the only drug that works\n\n2/10/09\nPurpose/intent of new order set or change:\nRemoval of Haldol from the Altered Level of Consciousness order set\nAddition of cardiac warning and monitoring orders being added to the Restraint IP and ED orderset\nTo promote the safer use of haldol and improve the management of delerium and agitation in our hospitals.\n\nBackground information/context setting, rationale for change:\nLast year the FDA issued a warning on the use of Haldol.  (For details see: http://www.fda.gov/CDER/DRUG/InfoSheets/HCP/haloperidol.htm)  The attached orderset is the product of a workgroup convened by Regional P&T to address this issue as well as the more general issue of delerium and agitation in the hospital and emergency department.\nhttp://www.fda.gov/CDER/DRUG/InfoSheets/HCP/haloperidol.htm',NULL,'1198083855?M185768?Audrey E Barraza\n\nReassigning?1198870698?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\nPer Minh Nguyen 12/21/07: Here is the link to the FDA site: http://www.fda.gov/cder/drug/InfoSheets/HCP/haloperidol.htm\nAlthough haldol is not approved for IV use, the FDA does recognize that the IV route is frequently use.  My interpretaton of this is that, ECG monitoring is recommended if given IV.\nExcerpt:\nBecause of this risk of TdP and QT prolongation, ECG monitoring is recommended if haloperidol is given intravenously. \nPlan: forward to Dr. Trupti Mehta for regional P&T recommendation on use and monitoring 9done 12/28/07)?1199293551?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\n12/31/07: per Trupti Mehta, Regional P&T: IV Haldol in the setting of comfort care is used only as a last resort to control end stage delirium. At that point the concern regarding QT Prolongation is moot. \nOur palliative care NP Erin Crawford is reviewing this issue with the Regional Palliative Care team and based on their recommendations we can proceed. \nMy personal view point is as above.\nI will keep you up dated as I find out more.  \nPlan: await response from regional Palliative Care team, act accordingly.?1199924337?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\nRequest for review sent to Chair of Palliative Care chiefs for recommendation by Trupti Mehta, MD>?1201733020?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\n1/13/08: Shelley Garone, MD, Med Director Palliative Care NVLY provided response; ECG haldol monitoring at end of life not recommeded. Need further IPD or P&T recommendations for other order sets: Haldol Orders 414462\nALOC HBS 414350\nRestraints 413995?1203005093?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\nReceived confirmation of regional P&T recommendation: The Regional recommendation is that there be telemetry monitoring with the IV Use of Haldol except for the comfort care orders.   Trupti Mehta\nPhone; 510 784 4967.\nPager: 510-751-2019.?1203005490?H521379?Tina H Hamilton\n\nReceived regional P&T recommendation from Trupti Mehta: The Regional recommendation is that ther',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2233,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Lorna Yamaguchi','',2295762,NULL,'OS REV ICU Non-Invasive Ventilation 414156: change the CPAP wording inside of ( CPAP ) orderset',NULL,'SR',NULL,'0',NULL,NULL,'L','0','M','D','',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NICE','Res','0','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Conten