y assessment can lead to a dose of ativan, this can be considered a range order for medication.  \n\nAlso because there is not any clarifying language, the patient could be assessed every 15 minutes or every 30 minutes depending on how a nurse understands the order.\n\nSuggestion:  change them all to every 15 minutes or give indication of when assessment can be reduced to every 30 minutes.<BR><BR>2008-07-01 - Tina H Hamilton - Tina H Hamilton\n\n6/9/08 email from Kathy Cagney: \nI did discuss this with the group, just forgot to change all instances to every 15 minutes.  Please go ahead and make that change for me, thanks!\n\nThanks,\nKathy\n\n7/1/08 TIGR team review of request, CIWA Ar (revised) scoring, almost identical to current flowsheet and guidelines. Discussed options for 1) new order set or 2) adding special dosing for acute withdrawal (scale A-scale B) to current order set. Need to discuss w/ B Hoberman and new order set sponsor(s). Sherry Ellis to follow up.<BR><BR>2008-09-30 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review: status, team agreement to draft a new build; \nemail to Kathy Cagney\nHi Kathy,\nNow that North Valley is live and PRL is in production, our build/pharmacy team is beginning to build order sets that have been pending resources.\n\nOne is the ACUTE Alcohol Withdrawl order set; \n\nMinh Nguyen agrees to build out a draft with the build team, based upon the email agreements and documentation submitted below. Any questions will be forwarded to you for clarification.\nWhat is the source document for the CIWA ar score? \n\nCan you please provide the exact protocol URL or the document that would be posted? \nSorry, if you have sent before, I dont have it in Remedy or on the email chain below. If you have any questions, contact Minh Nguyen.<BR><BR>2008-10-06 - Jeremy D Vang - Started building the non-meds OS section in PROD.  Had quesiton regarding the CIWA URL hyperlink.  Discussed with Tina, she found a CIWA- AR protocol on the web and sent out communication