 Cagney:\nHi Barbara, all,\n\nWe discussed the issue whether the protocols associated with the Lepirudin and Argatroban order sets should be pharmacy driven or nursing driven at the Regional Critical Care Chiefs and Managers meeting on September 10th.  There was strong consensus from the group that we would prefer that pharmacy do the dose adjustment calculation, and relay the new dose to nursing to make the change.  \n\nThe rationale for this decision:\n\nThe relative rarity of use of the drugs will mean unfamiliarity with the protocols.  \nThere are times the drugs are used outside of the critical care areas.  \nThe concern is the unfamiliarity with the protocol and the many patient care activities and potential distractions that the staff nurse at the bedside has to deal with.\n\nTo summarize this email stream and capture the timeline of events:\n\nOriginally the protocols called for nursing to calculate any dose adjustments.\nThe order sets and protocols were sent out for review by various stakeholders.\nSome pharmacists felt the protocol should be pharmacy driven rather than nursing driven.\nThe Critical Care Domain agreed with this proposal at their September 2nd meeting.\nThe proposal was taken to the IPDs peer group meeting after the CC domain meeting, and they proposed having nursing drive the protocol, but double check it with pharmacy.\nBoth proposals were discussed at the Regional Chiefs, and there was consensus that the Nurse Managers and MDs would prefer the protocol be pharmacy driven.\n\nThe question now is what is the next step?  Who is the correct person or group to make a final operational decision on this issue.  Once this has been resolved the order sets and protocols are ready to be released.\n\nThanks,\nKathy<BR><BR>2009-10-02 - Jung M Lee - IPD group discussed issues this week.  Leaning towards building as argatroban per pharmacy, as pharmacy-driven protocol.  Based on this decision IPD group still needs to discuss further on how to implement it as per pharmacy protocol.<BR><BR>2009-10-06 - Jung M Lee - Email from Doug OBrien, KPNC regional director for inpatient pharmacy services:\nWe discussed the argatroban/lepirudin order sets at the IPD Meeting on Thursday (10/1).\n\nThe IPDs reached consensus and would prefer that these order sets be changed and structured as \"per pharmacy protocol\" order sets.  \n\nThis will require several additional actions:\n\n1.  A \"per pharmacy protocol\" for argatroban/lepirudin dosing will need to be created.  Several volunteers have already begun work on the protocol.  This will entail double checking with the lab on the current control value (or mean value) for the aPTT to ensure the current dosing nomograms are still accurate.\n\n2.  The KPHC order sets will need to be modified, i.e. the starting dose should be left in the protocol, but the subsequent dose adjustments will be \"per pharmacy protocol.\"  A pharmacist will calculate each dose adjustment and enter it into KPHC.  The nurses will subsequently double check the dosing using the established HAMP Process.\n\n3.  The pharmacist protocol will need to be approved by each local P&T Committee.\n\n4.  The staff pharmacists will need to be trained on the new protocol.\n\n5.  In the interim, the staff pharmacists in San Francisco will begin monitoring any current patients on argatroban/lepirudin focusing on optimizing the operational details, e.g. flow sheets, handoff between pharmacists, utility of the current dosing nomograms, etc.\n\nAll of these actions will take some time to complete, so I dont have an exact kick-off date.\nThe \"per pharmacy protocol\" should be complete in approximately 2 weeks.<BR><BR>2009-10-23 - Jung M Lee - Protocol in progress by the IPD group.  Expect P&T approval around dec/jan for pharmacy protocol.<BR><BR>2009-11-02 - Jung M Lee - Protocol still being created by the IPD group.  Plan for P&T around dec/jan.  Final date to be determined.<BR><BR>2009-12-18 - Jung M Lee - Followed up on t