t\n\nCreate order in the Standard Admission Peds and Standard Admission PICU order sets that allows an RN to link to the Pediatric Emergency Medication Sheet and print this sheet out to post at the patients bedside.\n\nThis order would belong in the Nursing section. \n\nOrder details should be \"Select link to the Pediatric Emergency Medication Sheet, fill in the patients weight in KILOGRAMS, print the resulting sheet and place at the patients bedside\"\n\nName of Order Set:	\nupdated list of impacted order sets 12/2/10, Per email Dan Brugger \nPeds Standard Admit\nPICU Standard Admit\nPeds Surgery Admit\nPeds Neurosurgery Admit\nPeds Head & Neck Admit (preselected)\n\n\nPurpose/intent of order set:\n<    >  To provide a ready, weight-specific reference for Pediatric Emergency Resuscitation Medications.\n\nBackground information/context setting:\n<    >  Quick access to ready, weight-specific reference for Pediatric Emergency Resuscitation Medications will improve patient safety and quality and efficiency of care by ensuring that this information is available in the even of an emergency.  It has already been used with great success and SCL and other facilities throughout Northern and Southern California. \n\nPhysician Sponsor Name:\nJon Feldman, MD\n\nDomain/SUIT that has approved the content:\nPediatric Domain',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2008-08-20 - Tina H Hamilton - 7/31/08 email to Ann OBrien, Lisa Rohr, Rosalba Carrillo-Vassel, Emily C Foo, Bill Yee, Kathryn Blake\n\nHello All,\nIs it possible for us to get a meeting together so we can discuss the status of the Pedi Emergency Medications dosing guidelines and determine a timeline for implementing? There were several key pieces of work and Im not sure that we collectively have a sense of task ownership and any deliverables/timeline. Notes below, but can we meet maybe Mon or Tues pm next week?\n \nEmily Foo and I spoke on Tuesday; she says that there are some confirmations re: drug doses still pending. \nDosing calculations: formulas correct, but several questions of range pending from Emily Foo; get source file from SCL pharmacy if possible (Esther, Ernest at SCL)\n\nLisa and Ann, Lisa provided screen shots of how this will appear in the MAR toolbar (see screenshot below). And per Lisa, there is already a link to the MicroMedex dose calculator.  The Pediatric Emergency Medication Calculator could live beside it.\n(Domain/Nursing: confirm workflow and where the document will be viewed and printed)\n\nRosalba, assuming that you receive a file with the correct content, someone on the IT side can program? Im not sure what is involved with that, so could use your perspective on what is needed to have this done.\nRosalba: confirm programming plan (convert from Excel)\n\nAnn, this would need to go through formal governance; Pedi and PICU domain approval of the link, appearance in the MAR toolbar etc, nursing review of the workflow, and then med center scrutiny by both PED and PICU local leads/stakeholders.\nWe would do that after we have a build draft. Anything you can suggest? Do we involve Kathryn R Blake at this point or once weve lined our ducks up?\n\nNo responses to meet received except from Kathryn Blake. \nSpoke with Lisa Rohr who reports SAC has a local calculator.\n\n8/20/08 Follow up email sent to group\nHello All,\nI spoke with Lisa Rohr last week who reports that the SAC PICU domain nurses have had an opportunity to review the request to build the Pedi Emergency Dosing Guidelines and currently have a local calculator which is working well. So at least from the SAC PICU perspective, this may be not needed right now? (Kathryn and Lisa, let me know if Im off here.)\n\nIf you are working on this please update Remedy comments and also perhaps we need a small group meeting to confirm understanding of work and timeline so that we can plan in advance for governance?\n<BR><BR>2008-11-05 - Tina H Hamilton - 8/20/08 From: Tina Herrmann-Hamilton\n    Sent: 08/20/2008 06:01 PM PDT\n    To: Lisa Rohr; Ann OBrien; Rosalba Carrillo-Vassel; Emily Foo; Kathryn Blake; Bill Yee\n    Cc:  Brian Hoberman\n    Subject: Fw: Project Planning: Pedi Emergency Medications Dosing Guidelines\n\nHello All,\nI spoke with Lisa Rohr last week who reports that the SAC PICU domain nurses have had an opportunity to review the request to build the Pedi Emergency Dosing Guidelines and currently have a local calculator which is working well. So at least from the SAC PICU perspective, this may be not needed right now? (Kathryn and Lisa, let me know if Im off here.)\n\nIf you are working on this please update Remedy comments and also perhaps we need a small group meeting to confirm understanding of work and timeline so that we can plan in advance for governance?\n\n8/20 confirmed by Kathryn Blake that things are OK in SAC without the calculator.\n\n11/5/08 sent email to domain leads:\nI want to bring this Service Request back to the Pedi Domain for confirmation of intent to pursue this request or close it as unneeded.\n\nIf the domain physicians and nurses agree to add this calculator, we can work with resources to build and host the hyperlink and then provide within KPHC. There will be workflow aspects associated with the use of the calculator. In addition to the technical aspects of adding to the MAR toolbar (as recommended by Brian Hoberman) we would want the domain to approve since information in the past indicated that this may not be needed. \n\nThank you, please let me know what the domain agrees to do. \n\n<BR><BR>2009-01-20 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review of new SR 3264166, Jon Feldman, to add pedi emergency med calculator. That duplicate SR has been closed, and the requestor of this SR changed to Jon Feldman. Note to Stevan Cavalier re: approval to build<BR><BR>2009-01-20 - Tina H Hamilton - Received final files from Ernest Yu, SCL IPD. Awaiting Dr. Cavaliers 2 week circulation then plan is to follow usual governance process for adding this new tool. Will require nursing review and updates to any workflows. Copied Nancy Aye and Craig Baker, CL, as heads up for java build and their input/questions/recommendations now.<BR><BR>2009-01-20 - Tina H Hamilton - removed obsolete attachment and replaced with 2 new files.<BR><BR>2009-02-03 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review; duplicate SR 3326655 resolved. Notes copied into details and summary. Reviewed past comments. Forward to Nancy Aye and Craig Baker for programming. Build team to explore placement of link in KPHC (MAR toolbar, PER, etc??)\n<BR><BR>2009-02-05 - Tina H Hamilton - Resent email to Brian Hoberman and Lisa Rohr requesting recommendations for how nurses will access link (MAR toolbar?).\nCopied Mark Knoblauch and Sherry Ellis<BR><BR>2009-02-05 - Tina H Hamilton - email Brian Hoberman\nThis belongs to Lisa and Bettianne. I support it.<BR><BR>2009-02-11 - Tina H Hamilton - Discussed with Lisa Rohr, Ruth Amos is the KPHC PICU nursing expert involved. All agree that adding the order to the orderset and the nurses will review and print from the PER is the immediate pathway. Longer term desire would be to add to MAR toolbar, which would make the Pedi Emergency medications dosing calculator available in all settings where pedi patients may present for care (ED, PeriOp, sometimes on Adult floors, etc.) This will require review and approval across domains and can be added later. Do not delay work on adding the order to the Pedi ordersets now.<BR><BR>2009-02-17 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review, needs EAP record for nursing communication order. EAP record has been ordered. Pending URL and Pedi domain nursing documentation of expected workflow. Plan, once URL  and workflow are available, to draft build and using Pedi domain description of workflow, circulate for review and comment. THis will print from PER. Using MAR toolbar is not the immediate scope.<BR><BR>2009-03-05 - Yoko Olsgaard - Following a long string of emails discussion rounding options, Craig released a test URL for the calculator. \nFinal decision was to calculate to 1 decimal place except where the rounding would cause some doses to be = zero - in which case the rounding will be carried out to 2 places.  Where an incorrect weight is entered (max is 100 kg) the calculator will set all calculated fields to zero until a correct weight is entered.  The calculator can be viewed and tested at this URL: \nhttp://cl-qa-new.crdc.kp.org/pkc/ncal/clib/tools/peds_emergency_meds_calculator/pediatric_emergency_meds_calculator.htm\n\nThis will be reviewed at the March 9 Pediatric Domain meeting.<BR><BR>2009-03-05 - Yoko Olsgaard - Ernest U has offered additional clarification regarding the Pediatric Emergency Meds Calculator.  The restriction on disallowing an inputted weight greater than 100 kg has been removed.  It is not the weight that is restricted but rather the maximum dose that is restricted.  Coding has been added to prevent the medications from exceeding their maximum dose limits regardless of what weight is inputted. \n\nThe calculator can be accessed at this URL:\n\nhttp://cl-qa-new.crdc.kp.org/pkc/ncal/clib/tools/peds_emergency_meds_calculator/pediatric_emergency_meds_calculator.htm<BR><BR>2009-03-09 - Tina H Hamilton - Nancy Aye requesting business testing and sign off, what is the process/\nemail sent to Nancy Aye re: governance steps. Domain leads (MD/nursing) approval is needed for the next steps to include review and comment of test link. Comments to be collated and sent to domain leads, could lead to additional java changes.\nRequested that Jon Feldman, Stevan Cavalier, Dan Brugger (and a nursing rep) provide approval for next steps with background/comment following their meeting.\n\n(Note, emails re: URL include references to ETT calculation. Dan Brugger requests that the meds dosage calculator not be delayed awaiting ETT. Need domain to signal when the current version is done.)<BR><BR>2009-04-06 - Tina H Hamilton - 3/31/09 Yolanda Lassiter assigned lead for testing. To coordinate with domain and testing team.<BR><BR>2009-05-04 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Yolanda Lassiter to domain leads:\nI am checking to see if we are ready to move forward with the Pediatric Emergency Meds Calculator?  The calculator was recently tested by an ED MD and RN, both have signed-off on the functionality. I understand most of you have tested the calculator as well.\n\nJon Feldman email:\nThis looks good to me.  But, Ernest U is much better at troubleshooting than I am.  Please do not release until you have clearance from him.\n\nErnest U email:\nPlease move forward.  Every drugs and defibillator settings in the web version are calculating according to our current Excel version.  I had also looked at the formula parameters (calculating dose and max dose) being used in the web script to be consistent with ours.\n\nFor reference, attached is the formula grid that detailed our current version. (attached)<BR><BR>2009-05-04 - Tina H Hamilton - Request for background/context from Jon Feldman. Next steps, review and comment once communicaiton is created.\n<BR><BR>2009-05-04 - Tina H Hamilton - Per Jon Feldman\nThere should be links to this reference in every PICU and Pediatric admit order set and every Pedi Procedural Sedation OS.  There are probably some ED and Anesthesia OSs that should have this link too.<BR><BR>2009-05-04 - Tina H Hamilton - Background/context received, see description<BR><BR>2009-05-04 - Tina H Hamilton - email Craig Baker\nCurrently the calculator is on the Clinical Library QA server.  This server is not accessible to the general Kaiser clinician population (unless youre given the direct URL to access the file as has been done during this testing).  Now that sign-off has been received, I will publish the calculator to the Clinical Library Production server.  Please allow 24 hours for the file to populate to that server before attempting to link to the new URL of:\n\nhttp://cl.kp.org/pkc/ncal/clib/tools/peds_emergency_meds_calculator/pediatric_emergency_meds_calculator.htm<BR><BR>2009-05-05 - Sean E Ryan - Sending screen shots out per request<BR><BR>2009-05-21 - Tina H Hamilton - Sent for review and comment; including domain leads affected by order set additions. Due 6/5 due to holiday. Plan for 6/17 HCG.<BR><BR>2009-06-05 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Medical center comments sent to sponsors with note saying all issues must be resolved by 6/9/09 in order to make the 6/17/09 HCG meeting.<BR><BR>2009-06-11 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - From Stevan Cavalier:  There are significant items to discuss based on comments in Excel table attached below.  Can we get into this on the Pedi and/or PHBS content calls today and/or tomorrow?  We should have (at least) Dr Feldman and pedi pharmacy representation on the call.  Also, since SAC/ROS has done a lot of work around the subject, and is the origin for many of the comments, someone from there should sit in too.  Im pretty sure we will need more time than well have (theres a pre-existing agenda), and likely will need to set up a workgroup to address the issues later on.  \n\nStevan\n\nBecause of this, we are pulling this from the June HCG until all issues are resolved.<BR><BR>2009-11-25 - Tina H Hamilton - Per Ruth Amos via email, PICU domain discussed this past week and will want a \"toggle link\". Sent email to Dan Brugger and Alice Hanson to provide details of approval, order sets to be added to, etc. Also, request domain AC to update Remedy  ticket with approval details.<BR><BR>2009-11-30 - Robbie Zampa - Updated Summary Description adding MCH PED/PICU descriptor<BR><BR>2009-12-02 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Dan Brugger, Ruth Amos\nThe Emergency Medication Sheet has been approved by Peds and PICU.  It incorporates both Broselow and PALS versions that will need to be selected by the user\n<file received, see attachment EMS Brpselow v2.3.xls)\n\nIt should go in as a link to the MAR with an order for the RN to \"Select Broselow or PALS as per facility standard, enter the patients weight in kilograms, print out and place at the bedside on admission.\"\n\nThese are the order sets recommended:\n\nPeds Standard Admit\nPICU Standard Admit\nPeds Surgery Admit\nPeds Neurosurgery Admit\nPeds Head & Neck Admit\n<BR><BR>2009-12-02 - Tina H Hamilton - Description updated per Dan Bruggers email. Requested that Dan Brugger provide the source file for calculations so that this can be sent to Craig Baker, CL java programmer<BR><BR>2009-12-02 - Tina H Hamilton - Requested approval from Chuck Meltzer, Tom Curran and John A Duncan to add to their respective order sets listed by Dan Brugger.<BR><BR>2009-12-02 - Tina H Hamilton - From Chuck Meltzer, HNS: Alrighty...opened and viewed and still do not ever imagine an HNS surgeon using any of these meds without pediatrics involved and ordering them, so I am not sure what we would do with them on our admission order set.\nPlan, remove HNS pedi order sets from proposal. Dr. Meltzer to indicate otherwise later.<BR><BR>2009-12-02 - Tina H Hamilton - Update, per Chuck Meltzer, add to HNS orders and preselect, added to description, Peds Head & Neck Admit\n<BR><BR>2009-12-03 - Tina H Hamilton - Ernest U provided calculator password \"boston\", sent to Craig Baker with note that Ernest U will be the code/dosing reference contact. 408-828-7294<BR><BR>',459,1070,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2293,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Stevan cavalier','',2787213,NULL,'OS PICU Admit 415689: revise CBNT/IBNT protocols, med dosing and Asthma Scoring tool',NULL,'OS',NULL,'Train',NULL,'0','L','R','H','D','CBNT/IBNT protocols  Asthma Scoring tool',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NOWRK','Pla','0','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Content','Order Set - MD','','M','N','N',' ',NULL,'NR',' ','N','PICU','0','0','0','0','0','0','0',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-12-22 12:04:44','2008-07-30 10:42:29',' ',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,'','','',988,NULL,201,201,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-05-26 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2008-12-01 10:07:00','2009-10-13 08:13:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OS PICU Admit 415689 : revise CBNT/IBNT protocols, med dosing and Asthma Scoring tool\n\nInterim basis, remove protocols and display meds per domain approval',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2008-07-30 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Dr. Cavalier shared with Emily Foo, pedi and picu domain\nUntil we sort this out (on our next PICU content call 8/5 and/or PHBS content call TBA), we need to remove reference to the CBNT/IBNT protocols - that is remove the links, and eliminate the first two orders in each group.  Emily needs to review the albuterol dosing recommendations, in particular make sure the suggested initial continuous albuterol dose is 0.5 mg/kg/hr with a range of 5-20 mg/hr.   \n\nMy feeling is that we can add language that suggests the CBNT/IBNT protocols linked to the orderset are decision support, and can be used as is or locally adopted or not.  Interfacility cooperation (and KPHC itself) should allow us to share such protocols, and they can go through local approval processes PRN.  \n\nI dont want us to feel obligated to make sure every  location has exactly the same policies and protocols in place (which in a way are a kind of decision support) before linking to them.  For instance, like the CBNT/IBNT protocols and asthma scoring systems, we refer to diabetic guidelines and precautions, pain assessment, anesthesia recovery scores, neuro status checks, coma scoring, etc etc in our order sets, though the exact methodology/systems used vary from place to place.  \n\nIn fact, linking to well-considered P/Ps give  local facilities ideas about what regional, multidisciplinary groups agree on as best practices, and can help them improve their own local P/Ps.  MDs ordering these protocols locally (first two orders in the CBNT and IBNT sections) will learn to do so only where such protocols exist.  \n\nI would like to make sure we have RN as well as pharmacy representation on our PICU and PHBS content calls to get this settled.  The PICU content call is 930-11AM 8/5.  1 866 258 0960  *1089402*  Webcast via QWEST:  www.kpconferencing.qwest.com.  \n\nStevan\n\nCopied Kathryn R Blake and Ann OBrien; mtg info for Kathryn and Emily to join\nPlan; interim removal of protocols then revise per domain agreements<BR><BR>2008-07-31 - Tina H Hamilton - Pending Screen revision from Emily Foo.\nNote the following request from Albin Leong to consider for revision:\nJust a suggestion to consider albuterol MDI via spacer/holding chamber for intermittent therapy in the order set.  There is a fair amount of literature about comparative efficacy of albuterol delivered by MDI-spacer/holding chamber vs. nebulization.  Many leading pediatric hospitals use this mode primarily in their EDs and hospitals.  It is also an option for acute asthma in the EPR-3 guidelines.<BR><BR>2008-08-04 - Tina H Hamilton - Interim screens circulated by Emily Foo and approved by Stevan Cavalier and Kathryn Blake. Phone message and \"cc\" email to Dr. Schiff and Dr. ONeil to determine release date based upon local MEC approval. Meeting to further discuss content scheduled 8/5/08.<BR><BR>2008-08-05 - Tina H Hamilton - email per Albin Leong in response to screen shot:\nThis continuous dose looks good, with the current appropirate EPR-3 guideline albuterol dosing/weight & maximum dose.  For the intermittent, if that is also being discussed, the group, especiallly the intensivists, should discuss what they think their default should be.  Might I then suggest a drop down menu to include different frequencies such as  q20min, q 1h, 2h, 4h, q6h, *** and/or others, such as qid, q8h, etc.  The other consideration that might be discussed would be levalbuterol and albuterol MDI/spacer dosing.\n\nAlbin\n<BR><BR>2008-08-05 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Dan Brugger in response to screen shots:\nLooks good to me Emily.\n\nDan\n\nDan Brugger MD,MPH\nPediatric Hospitalist\nSouth Sacramento Kaiser Medical Center\nAssistant Inpatient Chief of IT SSC\nAssociate Lead NCAL Region Physician Training Inpatient KPHC\n<BR><BR>2008-08-07 - Tina H Hamilton - Per Marc Schiff and SAC team, OK to release changes today and follow up with MEC next week. Notified site that changes will be visible at approximately 5:00 pm, copied to Addileigh Porter, Emily C Foo/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Kimberly M Black/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Marc Schiff/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Dan L Brugger/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Stevan Cavalier/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Brian Hoberman, Kathryn R Blake/CA/KAIPERM@KAIPERM, Ann OBrien<BR><BR>2008-08-12 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Marc Schiff confirming SAC MEC approval of order set.<BR><BR>2008-09-05 - Sherry J Ellis - Links referencing the IBNT and CBNT protocols have been removed.  Tina HH. states in her email of today \"This SR is referring to the revision of the order set; to include changes to the protocols, dosing, etc. Kathryn Baker and Emily have held at least one mtg with the PICU docs, so keep this open to capture the changes for the next version.\"<BR><BR>2009-05-26 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review, per Emily Foo, orders changed and no protocol links in place. Need to know if the domain is satisfied with this or actively working on new protocols. Referred to Ru