apy \nMech Vent 414158\nStandard ICU Admit 414120\n\n\nPED\nNew OS Cystic Fibrosis\n415691 Peds Ventilator\nplease see comments 3/9/09 (see email dated 2/10 - Y Olsgaard from Pedi domain -\nIf the Sputum induction order is a distinct order and can be ordered a la carte, it does not need to be put into the Peds Ventilator orderset but if it is NOT a la carte it needs to be put in the new Cystic Fybrosis Orderset that the Peds Regional Domain is working on right now and the Peds Ventilator OS.)',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2008-10-28 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - TIGR Reviewed.  Send to Herb Szeto & Anne Foss-Durant for domain discussion of workflow and how they want to order sputum induction.<BR><BR>2008-11-07 - Tina H Hamilton - email received from Anne Foss Durant; approves of build teams recommendation to add the RT sputum induction orders to ordersets with sputum culture orders (as shown on screen shots ). Anne manages RT and understands the issue. Workflow for RTs is unclear; do they use the PER to done orders? Anne will follow up on RT practice. Agrees that these are LAB orders and need to route per current flow.<BR><BR>2008-11-07 - Tina H Hamilton - Will require analysis of sputum culture orders; and cross domain approval to add the RT smartgroup to the various impacted ordersets.<BR><BR>2008-11-07 - Tina H Hamilton - Request sent to Sherry Ellis to analyze ordersets with sputum cx orders so this request can be forwarded to impacted domains.<BR><BR>2008-11-11 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review; confirmed HBSapproval but need for \n\nPneumonia HBS\nCOPD/Asthma HBS\nSepsis 414364\nFever HBS (gram stain) 414111\n\nTina to fu with domains beyond HBS for approval. WF: hypertonic saline orders are PRN and will be on the MAR. The orders are LAB orders; nursing to follow current WFs of attempting to collect or notifying RT when appropriate.\n\nED\nED pneumonia 414303\nEarly Goal directed Therapy \n\n\nICU\nEarly Goal directed Therapy \nMech Vent 414158\nStandard ICU Admit 414120\n\n\nPED\nNew OS Cystic Fibrosis\n415691 Peds Ventilator\n\nNICU \nPatient Decompensation NICU 414245\n<BR><BR>2008-11-14 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Per Dr. Yamaguchi, this will be referred to the domain for discussion.\n<BR><BR>2008-11-17 - Tina H Hamilton - emails sent to Ped (Dr. Cavalier and Kathryn R Burke), NICU (Drs Fischer, Ziegler and Catherine D Parsons), ED (Christina Shih, Rob Norris and Laura Gittleman) to request domain approval to add Rt orders to their respective ordersets. Pending approval.\n\nNote sent to Herb Szeto and Anne Foss-Durant and Rohanna Heredia re email forwarded to domain members for NEW orderset. Clarified clincon team builder recommendation to add orders to existing ordersets. IP team member to attend domain meeting to describe purpose of change if desired.<BR><BR>2008-11-18 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Approvals so far:  ED RN & MD, M/S RN, Crit Care MD\n\nIn our ED nurses do not do this, they would call an RT, so it would not affect their workflow. I am not confidant I speak for all EDs. I can query our peer group (well attended) this Friday when we meet and let you know the group perspective.\nLaura Gittleman, RN, MBA (ED)\n\nWe will refer it to the domain for discussion. \nLorna Yamaguchi MD (ED)\nAssistant Physician in Chief\n\nI approve. Christina Shih (Crit Care MD)\n\nApprove  Anne Foss-Durant, NP, MBA (M/S RN)<BR><BR>2008-11-20 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Comment from Rob Norris:\nI have mixed views.  I agree with Christina that it is not likely to be used in the ED too much, and as such would tend toward leaving it off.  However, its not likely to cause any particular harm.\n\nMy only suggestions would be to a) definitely make clear which solution is used for which sputum induction (pneumocystis vs non-pneumocystis).\n\nAlso, in the original e-mail, there are three ordersets listed-- Pneumonia and Early Goal Directed Therapy I can see, but which orderset is meant by \"ED\"-- is this the ED General orderset?\n\n-Rob\n\nResponse from Christina Shih:\nI would NOT put this on the ED general order sheet.  It will be used so infrequently that we shouldnt add it to that set.\n\nResponse from Rob Norris:\nagreed-- would not put in the ED General orderset.  Limit to Pneumonia ED NCAL.\n\n-Rob<BR><BR>2009-02-10 - Yoko Olsgaard - Comment from Dr. Cavalier (Peds and PICU Domains) \nIf the Sputum induction order is a distinct order and can be ordered a la carte, it does not need to be put into the Peds Ventilator orderset but if it is NOT a la carte it needs to be put in the new Cystic Fybrosis Orderset that the Peds Regional Domain is working on right now.<BR><BR>2009-02-10 - Yoko Olsgaard - Adding to Comment from Dr. Cavalier - if it is not a distinct ordre that can be added a la carte, it also needs to be added tot he Peds Ventilator OS.<BR><BR>2009-02-11 - Yoko Olsgaard - NICU Domain Meeting results - not needed for NICU domain.  Not used enough.<BR><BR>2009-03-09 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Yoko Olsgaard:\nApproved to add to both the new Cystic Fibrosis OS, and to the PEDS Ventilator OS with the following correction for Pediatric patients. \n\nApproved with one change requested. \n\nDr. Albin Leong (Pulmonary/Allergy Pediatrics SAC) thought 15mL saline to induce is too high. 20ccâ€™s of 7%. \n4-5 mlâ€™s seems more appropriate according to SCL. This was verified with a phone call to SCL colleagues. \nDr. Brugger to forward Dr. Albin Leongâ€™s email to Tina. \n\nThe thought was that the volume of saline was based on adult doses. \n<BR><BR>2009-03-09 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Emily Foo to Sherry Ellis forwarded to goverance:\nHi Sherry and Sean, \n\nI dont believe there is a standard dose recommended for the induction.  The hypertonic saline is delivered as an aerosol via a nebulizer.  Hypertonic saline comes in 3%, 7%, and 10%.  The 3% and 10% comes in 15 mL container which would probably work if set as the default dose volume.   I would assume there would be a local protocol at each facility for