 at the deadline for sending out this communication and that it is a priority because of core measures we will move forward with the following:\n\n1)  Change the decision support in the statin section to \"Simvastatin (ZOCOR) is the generally preferred statin (at 40-80 mg daily).\n\n2)  The STATIN section will be added to the ACS and PCI ordersets.\n\n3)  We will defer from using the same STATIN section in the ischemic stroke orderset until we hear back from Neurology regarding a) whether the dosing decision support/recommendation is applicable and b) whether we even want it included in the subarachnoid orderset.  \n(Jeff, the proposed STATIN section will not have a default selected.  There will be decision support language instead that states that Zocor is preferred at 40-80 mg unless there is renal dysfunction.  Emily is working on restrictor logic that would eliminate the higher doses of Zocor if a patient had an elevated creatinine.  This is different from what is in the ischemic stroke orderset which defaults the dose to 80 mg and does not contain a hard stop.  My preference is to use the same section in the ischemic stroke orderset as in the cardiac ordersets.  Im not sure I see any reason for it in the subarachnoid hemorrhage orderset).\n\n4)  The ACE/ARB section will be added to the CHF, ACS, and Post- PCI ordersets.  There is a hardstop for both ACE and ARB but \"no LV dysfunction\" is available as an option for reason not ordered.  \n\nPhil, \nthe original intention for the ACE/ARB section was for the CHF and ACS ordersets when this was originally brought forward to HBS and Med-Surg Domain.  We can hold off from adding it to the PCI orderset if you want to discuss it further with your group.  Please let Tina know today if that is the case otherwise the communication will go out with PCI included.\n<BR><BR>2009-03-11 - Tina H Hamilton - email Phil Lee\nI am OK with everything below. lets include ace/arb section on post-PCI order sets.  the documentation is likely important since HBS or other physicians may be less likely to see post pci pts in the hospital prior to discharge. if we get alot of feedback later, well reassess.\n\nfor Jeff Klingman and others: heres the rationale of decision support language from Cardiology perspective:\n\nive coordinated the statin language with Eleanor Levin, representing the PHASE group. here is the rationale for 40-80 mg dosing recommendation.\n\n--we really want to push for 80  mg daily whenever possible (to get those LDLs down!)\n--a lower dose (of 40 mg or 20 mg daily) should be started for elderly and those with MILD renal insufficiency\n--we already have language in decision support re: when to use pravachol and what to do in setting of severe renal insufficiency\n\nwe have 80 mg zocor order ranked 1st to promote that practice\n--40 mg option is 2nd for those pts where physicians are concerned\n--alternative drugs and doses below those\n\nAgreement on this language seems consistent with our practice without having SO MUCH decision support that no one will read it.<BR><BR>2009-05-14 - Tina H Hamilton - SR forwarded to Kamran Sahrakar for final determination of subarachnoid order set.<BR><BR>2009-06-24 - Tina H Hamilton - Reviewed draft build within Neurosurg Supplemental Order set with Neurosurgeons. changes: \nAdjust infusion rate inst (CVP 5-10, PAD 13 -20)\nMedications; Add Normal Saline IVF, 80 mL/hour\nOral meds; add NG route as option\n\nPlan; circulate changes 6/26/09<BR><BR>2009-09-04 - Thomas Chun - k.sahrakar approves build - schedule for nov hcg as an update to supplemental neuro os.<BR><BR>2009-11-02 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - planned HCG changed to 12/16/09, planned release to 1/26/10, build incomplete.<BR><BR>2009-11-11 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Changed to medium level of governance change since these changes are in place for other order sets.  Approved by Dr. Sahrakar.  Scheduled for release on 12/22/09.<BR><BR>2009-11-11 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Change comm sent to