9-09-16 00:00:00','2009-08-19 00:00:00','2009-08-20 00:00:00','2009-09-03 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-09-07 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-09-09 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','2009-09-21 00:00:00','2009-09-23 00:00:00','2009-09-23 00:00:00','2009-09-23 00:00:00','2009-09-23 00:00:00','2009-09-23 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-04-01 03:38:00','2009-09-23 05:07:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OS Rev Multiple; removal of CK-MB and aPTT/PTT\n\nSelective replacement of CK and CK-MB orders with troponin order:\nWe were asked by Regional Lab to review the order sets to develop consistency with KPNC ACS Guideline regarding cardiac markers used to assess for myocardial injury and myocyte necrosis (i.e. myocardial infarction). Historically, CK and CK-MB have been the markers used. In 2007, the Joint European Society of Cardiology-ACC-AHA-World Health Federation Task Force established troponin as the biomarker of choice for this purpose. The KPNC Acute Coronary Syndrome Team has also adopted this perspective.\n\nAs such, in general, the order sets should be reviewed to see where it is appropriate to replace the orders for CK and CK-MB, with troponin. This is especially relevant for post-surgical patients where there is a greater likelihood that elevations in CK and CK-MB are the result of skeletal muscle injury rather than myocardial injury. For some cardiac patients, it is reasonable to leave the option of ordering CK and CK-MB since this may supplement \"sizing\" of an MI (when used in conjunction with troponin I measurement).\n\nElimination of aPTT or PTT orders as a \"routine\" baseline measurement OR as a method to monitor efficacy of heparin:\nRequest is to review all ordersets and remove the aPTT and PTT orders as obtaining this baseline is no longer clinically useful (except in the case of clinical concern about hypercoagulable state....on ordersets specific for that, leave the aPTT or PTT orders, though should change to ONE standardized way of naming it: either aPTT or PTT).   In KPNC, we NO LONGER use PTT to adjust heparin dosing. Rather, we use anti-Xa. \n\nAs a reflex (ie fall back to previous practices), physicians routinely check off PT/INR and PTT for many patients (e.g. preop, on admission to hospital, etc)....in case heparin might be used later. There is no value in checking baseline PTT (or anti-Xa for that matter) prior to initiation of heparin.',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2552,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Phil Lee','',3512524,NULL,'OS Multiple: revise, remove aPTT/PTT',NULL,'OS',NULL,'0',NULL,'0','L','R','H','D','PTT aPTT',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NICE','Res','CARD','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Content','Order Set - MD','','L','N','N',' ',NULL,'NR',' ','N','MEDSURG','CCARE','ED','0','0','0','0','0',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-12-03 08:01:38','2009-04-01 15:58:29',' ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',959,NULL,95,201,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-04-07 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-04-01 03:58:00','2009-04-07 09:56:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OS Multiple: revise, remove aPTT/PTT\n\nElimination of aPTT or PTT orders as a \"routine\" baseline measurement OR as a method to monitor efficacy of heparin:\nRequest is to review all ordersets and remove the aPTT and PTT orders as obtaining this baseline is no longer clinically useful (except in the case of clinical concern about hypercoagulable state....on ordersets specific for that, leave the aPTT or PTT orders, though should change to ONE standardized way of naming it: either aPTT or PTT).   In KPNC, we NO LONGER use PTT to adjust heparin dosing. Rather, we use anti-Xa. \n\nAs a reflex (ie fall back to previous practices), physicians routinely check off PT/INR and PTT for many patients (e.g. preop, on admission to hospital, etc)....in case heparin might be used later. There is no value in checking baseline PTT (or anti-Xa for that matter) prior to initiation of heparin. \n\n\nthis is the rationale for the suggestion.\nPhilip C. Lee, MD, FACC\nCardiologist, Kaiser Permanente Santa Clara\nClinical Associate Professor, Stanford University\n(408) 851-3312 Tie-line 8-401-3312',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2553,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',3514954,NULL,'Enhancement - Ordersets-recent pain order change (Dilaudid dose)',NULL,'OS',NULL,'0',NULL,'0','L','0','H','0','',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NICE','Res','0','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Content','Order Set - MD','','M','N','N',' ',NULL,'NR',' ','N','0','0','0','0','0','0','0','0',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-04-07 11:50:54','2009-04-02 10:46:52',' ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','','',984,NULL,201,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:0