orate section into existing Adult Transfusion order set).  This is to accomodate emergent workflows for OB/GYN, and ED Trauma massive bleeding episodes (see attached document)',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2009-05-29 - Sherry Ellis - Spoke with Dr. Richard Ray (requestor) about requirements for this build.  He agreed that this may work as a section within the existing Adult Transfusion Order set.  There is a regional protocol in the lab for ways of managing massive transfusion needs.  Our workflows would not support the order he writes at the end of the labs to \"discontinue protocol\".  I informed him that ordering the blood products and the lab would in essence be the way the physicians start the protocol, and discontinuing the orders is the way to \"discontinue\" the protocol.  There is no need for supporting hyperlink protocol doccuments, since it is the blood bank/ lab working off of a protocol, and that is not housed in HC.  It should be a simple build, keeping in mind the operations / workflows are for the facilities to resolve.<BR><BR>2009-06-02 - Sherry Ellis - Tiger review:  Since massive transfusion workflows act much like a code blue,  current workflows are done on paper then scanned into HC.  Mark/ Sherry will discuss with Dr. Norris (left a phone message).  Defer work on build until decisions made about this emergent workflow.<BR><BR>2009-06-09 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review, Sherry Ellis; email to Rob Norris, Richard Ray, Alex Locke and Elliot Morrison, requesting further planning/discussion of code workflow followed for massive transfusion.<BR><BR>2009-06-23 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review; reviewed email history with comments from OB, ED domains, sponsor and Brian Hoberman. To build new OS, specific to massive transfusion. email chain and paper order set version (from Richard Ray) added as attachments to capture details. \nBuild team to plan build/protocol format. Needs workflow planning/understanding for massive transfusion protocol initiation with lab.<BR>