and to ***\ndecrease lockout to ***\ncall covering MD\n\nPurpose of change:\nThe addition of steps and decision support within the PCA inadequate analgesia order. \n\nBackground of change\nBased upon the review and analysis of a cross domain Pain Workgroup, these changes are being made to help physicians provide clear and precise instruction of PCA escalation with analgesis is inadequate.',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2009-06-01 - Tina H Hamilton - See attachment for notes and comments about this change.<BR><BR>2009-06-01 - Tina H Hamilton - Screen shots circulated to workgroup members. Details of comments sent to Minh Nguyen and Maggie Mentakis to plan next steps.<BR><BR>2009-07-01 - Tina H Hamilton - Reminder to Maggie Mentakis, Minh Nguyen re: what the next steps are. Build per feedback? Schedule release as medium level change?<BR><BR>2009-08-11 - Tina H Hamilton - TIGR review, Tina HH to resend email chain to Maggie Mentakis for next steps.<BR><BR>2009-08-11 - Tina H Hamilton - 8/3 Sametime, Maggie Mentakis, to view email re: changes\n8/11/09 TC with Maggie regarding PCA changes; resent collated comments<BR><BR>2009-08-17 - Tina H Hamilton - Response from Maggie Mentakis still pending. Attempted to phone (cell phone message box is full): called and left message on clinic phone; not on same time; resent email reminder.<BR><BR>2009-08-26 - Tina H Hamilton - Changes approved by Maggie Mentakis: email to Minh\nAdd the following per clinical issues workgroup:\nGive the MD choices for the times in step 2 and step 3 (blue boxes in screenshot below).  The group recommended choices of \"30 min,\" \"1 hour,\" and \" *** \".  The group agreed that one hour may be too long of a time period to wait before initiating the next step of the orders\n\nPer Maggie, add decison support: \ndecision support should be at the bottom as it currently is.  Minh, do you know if there is any standard for increasing a PCA?  I can tell you what I have seen people do, but I personally just assess the patient if the analgesia is inadequate and go from there.\nMy recommendations would be, step one, incrementally decrease interval\nstep two incrementally increase dose\nstep 3 call MD\n\n\nWe are considering these to be medium level changes; that is, clarification of the current orders. The plan would be to send to the workgroup members, who are the domain leads for their approval. If approved, we can schedule without HCH but will certainly need to send a change communication with advance notice.<BR><BR>2009-08-28 - Tina H Hamilton - Screen shots sent for workgroup review. Additional changes circulated by Minh to provide view of decision support.<BR><BR>2009-08-31 - Minh X Nguyen - Working out details with physician leads.<BR><BR>2009-08-31 - Tina H Hamilton - Sent survey to Pain workgroup members, requesting domain and clinical issues response within one month: Use of fentanyl on regular units or monitored areas only.<BR><BR>2009-09-11 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Email to Domain Leads for approval of order set sent by Minh Nguyen 9/10/09.  Response from Anne Foss-Durant with approval from nursing.<BR><BR>2009-09-21 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Background and Purpose added to description.  Changed to high level of governance. Sent for review and comment  due 10/5/09.  Plan for HCG 10/21/09 and release 11/24/09.<BR><BR>2009-10-06 - Tina H Hamilton - Collated comments and sent to Maggie Mentakis. Request to change HCG date to November to allow time for workgroup to review. Also, more comments being collated from NVLY, due 10/6.<BR><BR>2009-10-07 - Tina H Hamilton - Comments collated and submitted to Maggie Mentakis who will review and recommend next steps for decision making. Since multiple content changes require more content finalization, this SR is being postponed from 10/21 HCG to 11/18 HCG with planned release 12/22/09.<BR><BR>2009-10-23 - Tina H Hamilton - Per Brian Hoberman: for users who save their own versions, ensure that each of the sections specific for syringe or