"high\" level changes and will require review and comment.\n\n<BR><BR>2009-06-26 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Dr Rudow: I just noticed a mistake I made in the requested changes I submitted for the single dose narcotic order set.  On the endtidal CO2 order  on Page 4 of my submission,  the last sentence should read \"Call anesthesia for respiratory rate less than ***.\" \n<BR><BR>2009-06-26 - Tina H Hamilton - email received from Dr. Rudow:\nThere is a difference between continuous and continuous telemetric pulse oximetry.   With plain continuous all that is required is putting a pulse oximeter in the room with the patient.  It does not necessarily include central monitoring.  With telemetry, central monitoring is a constant.  Both orders are needed, because there may be a situation when telemetry is not available for a particular patient.\n<BR><BR>2009-07-01 - Tina H Hamilton - Reminder sent to Maggie Mentakis and Kathy Cagney for domain/nursing review; pasero scale for LOC is new. Request reply by 7/8.<BR><BR>2009-07-02 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Maggie Mentakis, comments and questions regarding build. Mark Rudow and Kathy Cagney to respond.\nLooking through this document I have some questions/comments\nat the very top, number 1 in red there is a typo - should be after \"last\" not after \"least\"\nwe had a long discussion about what breakthrough pain medications should accomplish with the pain group, and most felt they should be fast acting to get the pain immediately under control.  I think it would be confusing if we use the same terminology for the oral and NSAIDS in this order set.  What type of language will you use to guide the nurse when to give these meds?  I assume they could be given ATC so wouldnt really call them breakthrough, but prns.  I think this also applies to the IV narcotics, unless you want a call when the pt receives 2 or more doses in an 8 hour period.  This may be the best for the IV.\nThe NSAIDs are smart groups.  We can make them show up only as they do in the other pain order sets - none for over certain age or elevated creatinine.  Dont recall off hand what parameters are used on the other pain sets, but Minh or Thomas could tell us.\nRe the Pasero Scale.  There will need to be considerable nursing communication before this goes into production.  Primarily adult services domain, since this will effect the floor/ICU nurses much more than the Periop nurses.  I will defer to Kathy, but this should be very well communicated prior to the change.\n<BR><BR>2009-07-09 - Tina H Hamilton - email Anne Foss Durant: We do not have a lot of epidurals in ICU here at AMC, but they do use the \"PASS\" scale for sedation.  KAthy may be a better resource. \n<BR><BR>2009-07-09 - Tina H Hamilton - FOR Med Surg domain discussion, next mtg<BR><BR>2009-07-27 - Tina H Hamilton - Inquiry to Herb Szeto, Anne Foss-Durant (cc Lorna Yamaguchi and Kathy Cagney) inquiring re: domain approval.<BR><BR>2009-08-10 - Tina H Hamilton - Inquiry Herb Szeto, domain leads, inquiring as to status and next steps<BR><BR>2009-08-11 - Tina H Hamilton - email from Kathy Cagney detailing Regional Epidural Project, policy/procedures, training and goals to maintain epidural pts on Med Surg units (not ICU). Pasero scale is included. Do we need a workgroup of domain and CASD/Epidural Project reps to finalize plans for the order set changes?<BR><BR>2009-08-11 - Tina H Hamilton - Note, per Vicki Casella-Gordon, DSA, a request has been submitted for copyright permission to use Pasero Scale in KPHC>National involved.<BR><BR>2009-08-27 - Tina H Hamilton - Note to Bettianne Wiessler and Barbara Norrish asking for process to keep activity on iNGG, ops and nursing communication open for follow up and eventual approval to build.<BR><BR>2009-09-10 - Tina H Hamilton - follow up email to Barbara Norrish; Bettianne suggests she is the contact, need timeline for PCS and KPHC to approve, so we can target potential order set release date.<BR><BR>2009-09-14 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - Status changed to pending support partner.<BR><BR>2009-09-14 - Tina H Hamilton - per email, Dr Rudow: Page 4 of my submission> Nursing orders > ETCO2 monitoring > Instead of \"Call Anesthesia for saturation less than **  It should read \"Call Anesthesia for respiratory rate less than *** or ETCO2 greater than ***)\n(Tina HH has added a note to the pdf build document, loaded as new build document.)<BR><BR>2009-10-16 - Tina H Hamilton - 10/16TC w/ Barbara Norrish. Pasero scale requires PCS approval and planning so suggest moving ahead with other changes to order set and then coming back to update pasero scale later. Other changes (do not give orders and related BPAs) are currently being analyzed so EAPs or workflows not yet fully approved or available for revision. Follow up note to Mark Rudow to inquire about what of the remaining changes should be done now.<BR><BR>2009-11-02 - Tina H Hamilton - follow up inquiry to Mark Rudow; plan to work on interim changes until pasero and \"do not give anticoag\" orders are ready, and if so, what changes to vital signs and notify physician are needed?<BR><BR>2009-11-03 - Tina H Hamilton - Mar Rudow asks \"My first thought would be to go ahead with all of the changes except the Pasero Scale and Do Not give orders.  That inclination would be tempered by two considerations.  First, how long will it take to get the Do Not Give and Pasero issues settled?  If we are talking about few weeks, then we should wait.  The other would be whether a physician would have to redo their defaults if the changes were done in two stages.\"\nNote to Sherry, Minh and Stephanie re: timeline for EAPs (new do not give anticoag orders), and what impact revisions will have on saved user defaults. \nPasero will be at least 6 months per Barbara Norrish.<BR><BR>2009-11-12 - Tina H Hamilton - Per Sherry Ellis: After an MD has saved a user order set, when we make changes to the base orderset, they are notified when opening their version the next time.  We indicate for them what the change was so they can either make the change in their version, or clear their defaults and create a new user saved version<BR><BR>',1064,1040,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2620,0,'N',1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Dan Brugger','',3722166,NULL,'Create new Pediatric Pain Order Set',NULL,'OS',NULL,'Stage',NULL,'0','L','N','H','D','Pediatric Pain',NULL,NULL,'','Emily Foo',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,'NICE','Wor','0','KPHC CN IP ORDERSETS',NULL,'End User Applications','KPHC Inpatient MD/CRNA/Midwife Content','Order Set - MD','','L','N','N',' ',NULL,'NR',' ','N','PED','0','0','0','0','0','0','0',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-12-22 12:05:58','2009-06-08 12:29:16',' ',NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,'','','',988,NULL,201,95,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-06-09 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00','1900-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2009-06-09 07:37:00','2009-09-03 12:50:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Create new Pediatric Pain Order Set\n\nExtract Pain section from Standard Admission Peds OS to create a new OS.  More build requirements to follow',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'2009-06-09 - Gail L Gordon Gaskins - TIGR Reviewed.  Pending build documentation.<BR><BR>2009-07-27 - Tina H Hamilton - Note to Dan Brugger re: SR 3843516 (BPA) and if it is related to this SR..and, if the build documents for this SR are still p